<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 TRASH TRIUMPH: East Ventura County residents are applauding a decision by 
Waste Management not to truck trash from the city of Oceanside to the Simi 
Valley Landfill (B6) . . . It's the latest go-round in a game of who gets trash 
from where. Though the Simi Valley dump has escaped the clutches of its 
neighbor to the south, Oceanside still has its eye on sites in Lancaster, 
Bradley and the City of Industry. 
</P>
<P>
 KICKING BARRIERS: They may be best friends, but when it comes to playing 
football it's every girl for herself. . . . Chrissy Sanford kicks for the 
Newbury Park High School football team and Joy Barry does the same for rival 
Thousand Oaks High (C8). . . . The 16-year-old juniors are part of a statewide 
trend -- 71 girls played varsity football in California last year, more than 
five times as many as in 1991. . . . Their skill on the field has snuffed some 
of the skepticism from spectators -- and teammates. Said Joy: "They've come to 
respect what I do." 
</P>
<P>
 COVER OF NIGHT: Some cyclists have discovered a new way to hit the road: after 
dark. (Ventura County Life, Page 8) . . . Mountain bike riders are taking to 
Ventura County trails at nightfall -- but with powerful battery-operated lamps 
to light the way. . . . Aside from the danger of riding into unseen objects -- 
say, a cow -- night riding offers special rewards. "It's so cool and quiet," 
said Paul Sailor of Ventura. "All you hear are crickets and the wind in the 
trees." 
</P>
<P>
 FIT AS A FIDDLE: For some exercise buffs, bulging biceps aren't everything. . 
. . That's why Shana Sable of Simi Valley gave up bodybuilding competitions a 
few years ago for a new kind of contest: fitness shows. Sable won a regional 
competition of Ms. Fitness America, and will represent California at the 
nationals in November. . . . Contestants are judged on -- you guessed it -- 
fitness, as well as strength, coordination and flexibility. Sable, 30, believes 
the popularity of the hybrid sport is growing. "It's definitely appealing to 
the masses." 
</P>
</TEXT>
