<HEADLINE>
<P>
PENINSULA HIGH POSTS 37 MERIT SEMIFINALISTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Palos Verdes Peninsula High School placed 37 students in the semifinals for 
National Merit Scholarships, the most of any school in the state and ninth 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
 The school, with almost 2,900 students, finished No. 1 in the state two years 
ago and third last year. Scholarship semifinalists are estimated to represent 
the top 0.5% of the national graduating class. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a lot of people working real hard," Principal Kelly Johnson said. "And 
the families really do support us." 
</P>
<P>
 There were 66 semifinalists among South Bay high schools. The students enter a 
pool of about 15,000 semifinalists competing for 2,000 scholarships, worth 
$2,000 each, to be awarded in the spring.  
</P>
<P>
 An additional 4,700 students will be awarded scholarships for meeting criteria 
of scholarship sponsors and educational institutions. 
</P>
<P>
 Semifinalists were chosen from more than 1 million juniors attending nearly 
19,000 U.S. high schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Students qualified for the semifinals by meeting several academic standards 
and by scoring highest on a test administered by the National Merit Scholarship 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
 Following is a list of the South Bay semifinalists: 
</P>
<P>
 Carson 
</P>
