<HEADLINE>
<P>
FINANCES: ASSESSING TAX FOR LIBRARY SERVICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An open letter to Gardena Mayor Donald L. Dear: 
</P>
<P>
 I cannot believe that Gardena, with its relatively solid tax base due to 
playing upon people's vices, has failed to follow Carson and Lomita in 
assessing a mere $28.50 per year, per house, to support library services. 
</P>
<P>
 The library system is the cornerstone of democracy.How can we hope to have an 
informed electorate at all income levels without adequate access to 
information. Instead of finding ways to keep the public out, we should be doing 
everything in our power to bring them in. 
</P>
<P>
 We complain about the youth who seem to have too much time with which to cause 
trouble. "They just aren't as good as we were" is the cry of generations who 
are old enough to be homeowners. However, we extended our school day, and week, 
by spending much time in the library. For $28.50 a year this household is 
willing to offer the same opportunity to today's youth. 
</P>
<P>
 It is time to do the right thing. Show a little political courage and 
leadership. Bring the issue back to the City Council and vote for extending 
library services. 
</P>
<P>
 RICHARD E. INGALLS 
</P>
<P>
 Gardena  
</P>
