<TEXT>
<P>
 The Small Business Development Center and Center for International Trade 
Development in Pomona have changed addresses and now offer expanded services. 
</P>
<P>
 The centers offer free support services and training to any ongoing or 
potential businesses and entrepreneurs. Services include counseling, workshops 
and business start-up orientation. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the centers have added computers equipped with CD-ROMS and laser 
printers, and a library with information on marketing, accounting, management, 
international business, resource lists, grant sources and supplier lists. 
</P>
<P>
 Jointly sponsored by local colleges and state and federal agencies, the 
centers have moved to 375 S. Main St., Suite 101, Pomona, and are open from 8 
a.m. to 5 p.m. * 
</P>
<P>
 A bookstore billed as "probably the largest Chinese bookstore on the West 
Coast" has opened in Monterey Park. 
</P>
<P>
 SUP Bookstore, owned by Sino United Publishing, will stock 45,000 titles in 
Chinese and English. The aim of the 6,000-square-foot store, at 111 N. Atlantic 
Blvd., is to promote Chinese culture and facilitate cultural exchange. 
</P>
<P>
 Offerings include subjects ranging from Chinese literature to children's 
books, cookbooks and economic texts. Patrons will also be able to buy 
periodicals from China, Hong Kong and Taiwan. California-based Chinese 
newspapers are also available. 
</P>
<P>
 Additionally, the bookstore will stock language tapes and videos, Chinese and 
Western stationery, Chinese stamps, greeting cards and electronic dictionaries. 
</P>
<P>
 One corner of the store will be developed for cultural activities such as art 
exhibits. SUP Bookstore also plans to start a mail-order service. Stock Watch 
