<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; ANTI-AIRPORT GROUP ASSAILS USE OF BROCHURES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A grass-roots organization trying to defeat a ballot measure that would 
replace the El Toro Marine Corps Air Station with a commercial airport is 
accusing backers of the measure, including eight cities, of violating the 
Political Reform Act. 
</P>
<P>
 Taxpayers for Responsible Planning, which opposes the airport, said it has 
lodged a complaint with the Orange County district attorney against the Orange 
County Regional Airport Authority, the El Toro Initiative Committee and its 
treasurer, Dana W. Reed, and the cities of Anaheim, Costa Mesa, Garden Grove, 
Los Alamitos, Newport Beach, Seal Beach, Stanton and Villa Park. 
</P>
<P>
 The group is complaining that the airport authority published a brochure 
favoring the proposed airport at El Toro, which backers of Measure A are 
distributing as campaign literature. 
</P>
<P>
 The group contends that because the airport authority received contributions 
of $1,000 or more from the cities listed in the complaint, it has become a 
pro-Measure A campaign committee and thus is required to file campaign reports. 
</P>
<P>
 "They should have filed a statement of organization and periodic campaign 
reports. They haven't done so, and we believe this violates the Political 
Reform Act," the group's spokesman, Jeffrey Adler, said in a prepared 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
 Garden Grove Councilman Mark Leyes, chairman of the airport authority, denied 
the allegations, contending that the authority's interest in building an 
airport at El Toro predated the initiative efforts and is entirely separate 
from any political campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have studied the issue of airport capacity in Orange County and agreed 
with other reputable organizations that John Wayne Airport is incapable of 
meeting future demand," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are not using public resources to promote the initiative," he said, adding 
that any brochures that Measure A backers have used in their campaign were 
purchased from the airport authority. LESLIE BERKMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
