<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: FULLERTON; HOUSING PROJECT OKD DESPITE OPPOSITION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council this week approved a controversial low-income housing 
project, despite opposition from dozens of residents who urged council members 
to reconsider. 
</P>
<P>
 During a five-hour public hearing Tuesday night, residents complained about 
the project's proposed parking layout, saying it would cause traffic problems. 
They also opposed the $3.6-million project's location and density. 
</P>
<P>
 The project, a 27-unit apartment complex and two-level parking structure, is 
proposed for 2200 E. Chapman Ave. and is being built by Douglas Chaffee and the 
Fullerton Interfaith Housing Development Corp. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents wanted the city to conduct a traffic study and prepare an 
environmental impact report to determine the effect the project would have on 
its neighbors, but city officials said the studies are not necessary. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's things you can control and things you cannot, but I don't want this 
in my back yard," said Joe Tatar, who lives across from the project site on 
Chapman Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Joetta Simmons expressed fear that illegal immigrants may move into the 
housing project and said "that should not be done." 
</P>
<P>
 City officials said prospective tenants will not be asked whether they are 
illegal because such a question could be viewed as discriminatory. 
</P>
<P>
 The Redevelopment Agency owns the property, which is valued at $780,000. It 
will give the developers a $405,000 grant and a $375,000 low-interest loan to 
buy the land. The loan is expected to be paid back in 30 years, city officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The city is loaning the developers another $155,000 for development costs, 
which must be paid back in 30 years as well. 
</P>
<P>
 Rents for the apartment complex's units will range from $426 to $655 a month, 
and tenants must earn less than $28,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
 Churches from throughout the city supported the project, saying it is needed. 
</P>
<P>
 Construction is scheduled to begin within months, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Said Chaffee: "This is going to be a model project for the city. . . . It's 
something that will benefit the community and we'll all take pride in."MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
