<HEADLINE>
<P>
INMATE SUES SHERIFF'S DEPT. FOR INJURY IN RACIAL BRAWL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE TAMAKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A prisoner is suing the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department, alleging his 
civil rights were violated when he was injured in a racially based brawl at the 
Pitchess jail in Castaic. 
</P>
<P>
 Bryce Kelly contends in a lawsuit filed Wednesday in Los Angeles Superior 
Court that sheriff's deputies failed to adequately supervise a "racially 
charged" atmosphere at the Peter J. Pitchess Honor Rancho on the afternoon of 
Sept. 21, 1993. As a result, a riot erupted during which Kelly suffered a cut 
to his left hand that nearly severed four fingers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 A spokesman for the Sheriff's Department said he had not seen the lawsuit and 
could not comment. 
</P>
<P>
 The jail has been the site of numerous racially based fights, commonly between 
Latinos and African Americans. As of May 9, sheriff's deputies had reported at 
least 52 fights at the jail this year, some involving as few as two prisoners 
and some as many as 1,000. 
</P>
<P>
 It was during a melee between African American and Latino inmates that Kelly, 
who described himself as belonging to both groups, was injured, said George T. 
Kelly, an attorney who represents Bryce Kelly, but is not related to him. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit, which also alleges medical negligence and names County-USC 
Medical Center as a co-defendant, further contends that despite recommendations 
by medical personnel at the hospital that surgery be performed immediately on 
Kelly's hand, six days passed before he was treated. 
</P>
<P>
 As a result, Kelly's fingers suffered permanent damage and now curl into his 
hand, the suit said. He has lost about half the movement in the fingers, his 
attorney said. A decision by the Sheriff's Department to send Kelly to 
County-USC for medical treatment, as opposed to a nearby hospital in Newhall, 
was also based on race, the lawsuit alleges. 
</P>
<P>
 Kelly, who is serving the remainder of his sentence at a different jail, is 
seeking compensatory and punitive damages and attorney's fees.  
</P>
<P>
 Authorities have sought unsuccessfully for a way to prevent racially based 
melees at Pitchess such as the one Kelly says he was injured in. 
</P>
<P>
 So explosive were tensions at the jail earlier this year, that the American 
Civil Liberties Union, historically a staunch opponent of racial segregation, 
said in January that separating prisoners by race may be the only way to defuse 
tensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
