<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEIGHBORS FILE SUIT TO BLOCK NORTHRIDGE DAY-CARE CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HUGO MARTIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Neighbors of a planned day-care center in Northridge have sued to prevent the 
facility from opening, saying the center would violate deed restrictions 
imposed on the residential community nearly 40 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in Los Angeles Superior Court by 33 Northridge 
residents, asks a judge to stop Fernando and Sherry Segre from opening the 
center in the 18000 block of Devonshire Street. The suit also asks for at least 
$25,000 in damages for each neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles City Council approved establishment of the day-care center in 
June after a lengthy, heated dispute among neighbors and council members. 
</P>
<P>
 Opponents, including Councilman Hal Bernson, who represents Northridge, said 
the center would turn the neighborhood into a commercial zone. But supporters 
said the day-care center, which would care for a maximum of 24 children, would 
fit into the neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
 Joseph Donaldson, who lives two doors away from the Segres, said he joined the 
lawsuit because he fears the day-care center will create a traffic problem on 
Devonshire Street as well as diminish his property values. 
</P>
<P>
 On Wednesday, Fernando Segre and his attorney said they had not seen the 
lawsuit but planned to fight it vigorously. The center is scheduled to open in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
 "They have no grounds to stand on," said Segre, referring to the plaintiffs. 
"We went through all the legal processes and we won." 
</P>
<P>
 A lawyer for the plaintiffs was not available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
 The suit contends that in 1956 the owner of what was then called Devonshire 
Village imposed restrictions on each of at least 34 lots to keep them uniform 
and "to make the land a desirable neighborhood." The lawsuit says the 
restrictions allow only residential and agricultural uses and a day-care center 
would violate those conditions. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit contends the center will cause "discomfort, annoyance and 
inconvenience" to neighbors and reduce their property values. 
</P>
</TEXT>
