<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: MAXVILL FIRED BY NEW CARDINAL PRESIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 St. Louis Cardinal General Manager Dal Maxvill, who failed to lead the team 
into postseason play his last seven seasons, was fired Wednesday by team 
President Mark Lamping, who has been on the job about three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 Lamping gave no specific reasons for the move, other than the fact Maxvill 
couldn't produce a winner. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think any of us were satisfied that we haven't had postseason play 
here since 1987," Lamping said. 
</P>
<P>
 Maxvill, who is signed through next season, will remain with the club until 
Oct. 5. The move left uncertain the status of Manager Joe Torre, hired in 
August of 1990. Lamping said the new general manager would have input in 
deciding Torre's future. Torre is also signed through 1995. Pro Basketball 
</P>
<P>
 The Chicago Bulls, having lost Horace Grant to the Orlando Magic, signed free 
agent Larry Krystkowiak, a 6-foot-9 forward who played with the Magic last 
season after stops in San Antonio, Milwaukee and Utah. 
</P>
<P>
 Jeff Weltman, the Clippers' assistant director of scouting, has been promoted 
to director of scouting. He succeeds Barry Hecker, who was recently named an 
assistant coach. . . . The Clippers also announced that trainer Keith Jones has 
signed a multiyear contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
 Roy Tarpley could be close to returning to the NBA and the Dallas Mavericks. 
Tarpley flew to a league-sanctioned drug treatment center in Van Nuys for a 
drug test and his next, and possibly final, step toward reinstatement would be 
a meeting with NBA Commissioner David Stern. College Basketball 
</P>
<P>
 Ken Turner, Ohio State assistant coach, suffered a heart attack while jogging 
and was in critical condition at Grant Medical Center in Columbus. He was 
stricken while running near his home in suburban Westerville. . . . Shareef 
Abdur-Rahim of Atlanta, one of the nation's top college prospects, said he will 
attend California. Hockey 
</P>
<P>
 No progress was reported in a five-hour bargaining session between the NHL and 
its players association, the fourth meeting in six days. Significant 
differences would have to be resolved in order to reach agreement by Oct. 1, 
the scheduled start of the season. Representatives of each side will continue 
to talk before the next formal meeting, scheduled for Monday in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
 Pittsburgh Penguin center Shawn McEachern will be suspended without pay for 
three games for slashing Washington Capital defenseman Calle Johansson in the 
Eastern Conference playoffs last April. McEachern was also fined $500, the 
maximum allowed under the NHL's collective bargaining agreement. 
</P>
<P>
 The New York Rangers are "getting closer" to a new contract with Mark Messier, 
General Manager Neil Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
 Smith refuted reports that the negotiations were held up by a change in team 
ownership. Miscellany 
</P>
<P>
 A poll of 134 coaches of women's sports revealed that participation in sports 
can help stop drug use, smoking and unplanned pregnancies for girls. According 
to the survey, 97% said female athletes are less likely to smoke than those not 
involved, 88% said that athletes are less likely to drink and use drugs and 
more than 90% said athletes are less likely to have unplanned pregnancies. 
</P>
<P>
 The North Carolina women's soccer team won its 89th consecutive game, 5-1 over 
North Carolina State, setting an unofficial record for the longest winning 
streak in college sports. It broke the mark of 88 set by the UCLA men's 
basketball team in the early 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
 Top Rank Inc. is suing rival promoter Don King over rights to heavyweight 
Lionel Butler. 
</P>
</TEXT>
